<TITLE> EU sees progress in Turkey talks, urges reforms </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 STRASBOURG, France, Oct 24 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The European Union said on Wednesday membership talks with Turkey may advance this year, urging the Muslim country to step up political reforms and expressing concern over human rights and relations with Cyprus. EU Enlargement Commissioner Olli Rehn said the bloc could open talks in two more policy areas with Turkey in coming weeks as part of accession negotiations, but the country's new government should embark on reforms urgently. "At least two chapters, consumer protection and trans-European networks, could be opened in the coming weeks," Rehn told the European Parliament during a debate on Turkey. He reiterated reforms should include more freedom of expression, civil control over the military, overhauling the penal code, and rights for women, children and trade unions. Turkey should also take steps to normalise relations with Cyprus by meeting its promise of opening its ports to vessels from that country. Ankara does not recognise the southern part of the divided island, which is an EU member. Rehn repeated his condemnation of attacks on Turkey launched by Kurds hiding across the border in Iraq, urging Turkey and Iraq to work out joint measures to end the hostilities. Turkey started EU entry talks in 2005 but is not expected to join the bloc before 2015, if at all, as some member states oppose its membersh
